  <static seed="94" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/FractionArithmetic/SubtractFractions110.pg">
    <statement><p>Subtract: <m>\displaystyle{ -1 - \frac{8}{5}}</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="11" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>-{\frac{13}{5}}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>When doing arithmetic with fractions, it helps to rewrite any integers as fractions:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ -1 = \frac{-1}{1} }</m></p>
<p>Next, to subtract a fraction, we need to find a common denominator. In this case, it is simply the second denominator <m>5</m>. We will change the first fraction to have the common denominator:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ \begin{aligned}\frac{-1}{1} \amp = \frac{-1 \cdot 5}{1 \cdot 5}\\ \amp = \frac{-5}{5} \end{aligned}}</m></p>
<p>Finally, we subtract the numerators and keep the denominator unchanged.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   -1 - \frac{8}{5}
        \amp = \frac{-5}{5} - \frac{8}{5} \\
        \amp = \frac{-5 - 8}{5} \\
        \amp = -\frac{13}{5}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>The answer to this question is  <m>\displaystyle{ -\frac{13}{5}}</m>.</p>
</solution>
